This involves a worry about the loss of a woman’s reputation, because other villagers might regard a divorced female as “having couchez avec qui” (Was she then with everyone?). This is a situation which is difficult to explain to anyone outside of the surrounding villages. The insults that this degrading action would promote from the surrounding villages can cause a woman to bear the extra burden of gossip……Bye bye. If YOU divorce me, I am dead in this village!
This anxiety related to facing a reputation more of a shameful nature as opposed to a devastated one, is a prime word of cultural wisdom grounding their decision making. If a woman feels that her self esteem is not strong enough, this can be an important bargaining tool to keep her from leaving her marriage. For all of these women, the ongoing issue is one where the woman’s welfare depends more on the holding onto their in-laws than their husbands. According to my female informant, a marriage a woman enters into after she has already had children might be harder to hold onto than other traditional marriages. It is here where traditional views of faithfulness are off balance. One woman’s husband, and family, had given up on her children and she believed that as long as she continued to appear faithful to him, then she would be able to maintain her marriage.
